Ten photos will never be enough to express my gratitude. (There will be a part 2) 
2022 really was an unexpected blessing…one that will remain engrained as a staple and pivotal year for me as an artist and influencer. I’m so amazed but also so grateful at everyone who is inspired and touched by my creations and I pray to continue to use my gifts to create positive change in my community and beyond. 
The partnerships formed and the collaborations with my artist friends are so important to me and as I look back through all the photos I am reawakened to why I do this! And I’m so thankful.

Big thank you to my supporters and collectors! And also all of the partnerships, articles, Ted talks and interviews I have had this year. @complexshop @victory @studiowest117 @graffitiheart1 @cle4equity @thisiscle @clevelandmagazine @bleacherreport @statefarm @urbancommunityschool @nba @nbaallstar @condadotacos @strongsvillemiddleschool @clepublicsquare

As I try to gather all the photos I can to sum up 2022. I’m reminded. And not reminded of my accomplishments…but I am reminded that I also lived life. I managed to be there for my family, my son, vacations, sports events, and more. I lived. 
So as I move forward into 2023 I want to remember the same. Projects will get bigger, schedules will be busier…but through it all we just can’t forget to live.
I love you all! See you in 2023 💕

It’s crazy to think I wasn’t born with this talent despite what anyone may think. Life took a turn for me when I was 17 and I broke my femur chasing a title and record in the long jump (which I achieved). However that injury took my attention off of my athletic abilities and successes and derailed  the path I thought my life was supposed to take. 
That’s how I was introduced to art…and I was horrible (one day I’ll show you all my early drawings 🫠) anyway I was redirected into a passion I never thought about until that injury. At the end of 2015 when my son was one, I started to teach myself how to oil paint….I promised him, myself, and my supporters to never betray my gift but continue to learn through all its twists and turns. But that’s just the tip of the iceberg on my story but just a reminder to myself and to all of you that you CAN get good at something later in life…you CAN be successful at whatever you decide to master…and it is NEVER too late to go for it. And most importantly, do it scared but do it anyway. Much love to you all 💕
.

What are ways you simplify your organization so you can remain creative in your craft?
here’s what I do now to simplify my organization but also not compromise my creativity:
1. Create a designated work space: this one’s obvious but important I find myself migrating around the house leaving trails of Stina every where when I’m not in studio…then I’m left with a bigger space than intended to take care of.
2. Use a planning system: From the girl who hates routine and checklists I’ve rewired my brain to appreciate them and I can’t lie…they’re a necessity. ESPECIALLY for us creatives.
3. Prioritize tasks: sounds like another no brainer but let’s be honest we would always rather create…and then we forget about important tasks that need to be done. 
4. Set Boundaries: create yourself some work hours! And find ways to separate work and personal life. Your creative time is yours! 
5. Declutter Regularly: that’s what I’m doing in this video…I get hyper focused on projects and leave everything chaotic until I’m finished. I’ve learned to at least declutter after every major project. 
As creatives I know the hard part is remaining organized while still wanting to do all things creatively but I’ve reached a new level of clarity when all other aspects of my business are running smoothly! 
So I hope this helps those of you who’ve been asking! 
.
.
.
.
.
#painterslife #artistlifestyle #artworkfeatures #artwork_in_studio #artistsupportpost #painterly

This is my son. And this painting is titled “His Story” it holds an even stronger meaning for me now than it did when I first started this. You see lately my son has been dealing with kids at his school making fun of his skin color, as a mother it broke my heart to have him come home on 3 different occasions to share this with me. But my boy (in all his black boy joy) has faced this adversity like I could not have imagined doing at 8 years old. He’s well educated on his history, where he comes from, and who HE IS. And although his feelings were hurt he chooses to educate his peers as to why they should not make fun of him. I am so proud of him, and I’m so proud to present this piece honoring my little boy as he paves a way in history and begin to share his story.
.
.

Do you see that scar? 🩹 .
.
I got this scar in 2005 after having surgery when I broke my femur. With this injury came life lessons, ones in which have molded me 18 years later. This injury took me through loss, anxiety, depression, confusion, pain...
.
This scar reminds me that I am human, one that experiences heart break and disappointment being misused or unappreciated..
But my scars also symbolize me overcoming, it symbolizes strength, humility, growth, desire, passion and so much more.
.
I cherish my scar...it is the visual representation of turning your “L”s into lessons. 
It’s the very reason I’m an artist today. 
We all have scars whether physical or mental. 
We often use those scars as excuses to stop us from moving forward, but sometimes those are just turning signals rerouting your life to something more profound and aligned with your purpose. .
.
Do you have scars? Wear them proudly that’s your badge of honor.
.
.
.
.
.
#oilpainter #artistsupportpost #painterslife #artworkfeatures

I think the struggle with most artist is finding a way to balance business with a skill that once brought us peace and joy. When our talent that once helped us escape life becomes a job, it’s an unfortunate fate to our peace of mind. And mental health is fragile. What I am working on for myself, is bringing back that joy to create while trying to stay grounded and consistent. I’m not sure what that looks like yet, but everyday I’m trying something new to bring back the enjoyment and balance of being a full time artist/entrepreneur and a creator. Yesterday I spent an hour creating a new sketch, and did it in my favorite place. Today I’ll do the same, and tomorrow, and the day after that…until peace and joy find me 💕
.

To make the right choices in life, you must get in touch with your spirit. To do this, you have to experience solitude, which most are afraid of. Solitude is where your spirit speaks clearly, it knows truths, it provides answers, it increases the power of discernment and awakens your intuition.
.
.
When I made this piece I was in a state of solitude, I wasn’t answering calls and text, those closest to me seemed confused by my separation. I needed that time with my spirit to bring forth all that I am meant to be. Sometimes you don’t know what’s happening until you’re through it, but accepting that time to and for yourself is necessary for elevation of mind body soul and spirit. .
.
That’s how “Intuition” was created! 18x36 canvas prints are available on: stinaaleah<dot>com

I’ve been away but not entirely! Only to reconnect with myself and be more present in my every day life. I’ve spent the last month and a half off of Instagram ditching the pressure of “staying relevant” and really enjoying being a mom and watching my son flourish in his sports and just taking care of my family. Sometimes being in the now is way more important to me than sharing every project, every brushstroke, and worrying about the right hashtags and algorithms. But I can’t lie and say I don’t miss all of you, thank you for letting me be human and do what I need to do in order to stay sane. 
Also I gotta give a shout out to my beauty squad! @ebonyg_ has me feeling like a goddess in these Jah Locs and now I don’t know how to act 😂 and my girl @mc.couturebeautyllc always and I mean ALWAYS slays my nails. I need them in my life forever 😂

This is a high energy workout room, and my mural is meant to bring motivation, encouragement, and determination to this space!

From concept to mural.

When I designed this concept in photoshop I had no clue what color scheme I would use (I also had zero plan for the doorway). I actually didn’t know until I spent a day in the exercise room just staring at my outline on the wall. That’s how things develop into masterpieces….you don’t always have to know each step, all the plans, just trust the process, trust yourself, trust your training, trust your instinct, and trust that you’re the professional that will get it done.

Over the weekend I was LIVE painting at the Women’s Health Fair & Empowerment Expo. When I think about women’s health, I always think about how we push through to help everyone else and often forget about ourself. I wanted to create a piece that amplified the power of our voice when it comes to our health and navigating the medical system. My piece was interactive in which visitors could write their stories or encouraging words on the speech bubbles. This was an amazing experience thank you @metrohealthcle and the many partners involved in creating such a profound event.

The real, I love what I do when it comes to my art career and my purpose and anxiety hits me hard when I cant always get to work the way I hope to…but I love these moments, I love showing myself what I am capable of. 
(Currently doing research and drafting/finalizing mural designs)
I hope one day my babies look back at everything I did and are inspired by my ability to take action, persevere, and figure shit out and I hope you all do too! 
My content may look a little different moving forward, but it’s because I want to be real with what it takes to make things happen even when you think you cannot. 
🥂Cheers to all of us persevering all 2024 and beyond!
